 from alan saturn cs swin oz au alan christiansen subject re sphere from four points organization swinburne university of technology lines seven one nntp posting host saturn cs swin oz au spworley netcom com steve worley writes bolson carson u washington edu edward bolson writes boy this will be embarassing if it is trivial or an faq given four points non coplanar how does one find the sphere that is center and radius exactly fitting those points i know how to do it for a circle from three points but do not immediately see a straightforward way to do it in three d i have checked some geometry books graphics gems and farin but am still at a loss please have mercy on me and provide the solution it s not a bad question i don t have any refs that list this algorithm either but thinking about it a bit it shouldn t be too hard one take three of the points and find the plane they define as well as the circle that they lie on you say you have this algorithm already two find the center of this circle the line passing through this center perpendicular to the plane of the three points passes through the center of the sphere three repeat with the unused point and two of the original points this gives you two different lines that both pass through the sphere s origin their interection is the center of the sphere four the radius is easy to compute it s just the distance from the center to any of the original points i ll leave the math to you but this is a workable algorithm good i had a bad feeling about this problem because of a special case with no solution that worried me four coplanar points in the shape of a square have no unique sphere that they are on the surface of similarly four colinear point have no finite sized sphere that they are on the surface of these algorithms being geometrical designed rather than algebraically design meet these problems neatly when determining which plane the three points are on if they are colinear the algorithm should afil or return infinite r when intersecting the two lines there are two possibilities they are the same line the four points were on a planar circle they are different lines but parallel there is a sphere of in radius this last case can be achieved with three colinier points and any four th point by taking the four th point and pairs of the first three parallel lines will be produced it can also be achieved by if all four points are coplanar but are not on one circle it seems to me that the algorithm only fails when the four points are coplanar the algorithm always fails when the points are coplanar four points being colinear coplanar testing if the four th point is coplanar when the plane of the first three points has been found is trivial an alternate method would be to take pairs of points the plane formed by the perpendicular bisector of each line segment pair also contains the center of the sphere three pairs will form three planes intersecting at a point this might be easier to implement steve spworley netcom com